{"author":{"id":"8e1777f58c0cfe5478428be8f9fcbfe90d25e44689578335da8fc2246fe0915a"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1445084080,"nonce":"rGcTlmzu8SuwDr9PTOdvd/FpriY=","metadata":{"github-id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDE0ODkxMjkwMw==","github-url":"https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/issues/332#issuecomment-148912903"},"message":"\u003e \u003e Different number of columns, different headers/comment lines. Thinking about it I don't know what is similar between them ;)\n\u003e \n\u003e Isn't that what metadata is good for?\n\nAre we talking about a new file type here? Shouldn't be a file type as strictly defined as possible?\nWhat do you gain from a new file type that has no defined number of columns, no definition of header/comments over the already existing tabular format?\n\n\u003e \u003e featureCount is even worse, as it does not mark the comment line with # or similar symbols. \n\u003e \u003e So we need to recognise Geneid 1:, which is not really unique. Also please consider what happens if this identifier is changing between featureCounts versions, for example to Gene-ID 1:. You need to have a new data type to detect this. Versioned datatypes are currently not supported.\n\u003e \n\u003e Well, if this happens, the featureCounts wrapper should introduce a new datatype (like GFF and GFF3 are not exactly the same ... yet on a certain level interoperable). I'm seeing this from the angle of the tool wrapper \"explaining\" what kind of data it is producing. If tools can register new datatypes, I don't see the harm of having a few hundred different datatypes.\n\nTools can not register new datatypes. Tools can change metadata (to some degree) of an already existing datatype. All feature count tools are producing files that are tab separated, I think this is the most common denominator :).","files":null}]}